
Prometheus & Grafana
Monitoring on EKS Cluster
Step-by-Step Commands Guide  |  Parts 1 – 4


PART 1 — EC2 Instance & Prerequisites Setup

Step 1.1 – Launch EC2 Instance (AWS Console)

#	Action	Command / Detail
1	Open AWS Console	Go to EC2 → Click 'Launch Instance'
2	Name the instance	Name: landing-transform  (your project name)
3	Select OS	Choose Ubuntu (latest LTS)
4	Instance type	t2.micro  (Free Tier eligible)
5	Create Key Pair	Name: landing-transform-keypair → Click 'Create key pair'
6	Network settings	Allow SSH (port 22) only — leave rest as default
7	Storage	Leave default storage settings
8	Launch	Click 'Launch Instance' → Wait for running state

Step 1.2 – Connect & Install AWS CLI v2

# Connect to EC2 via SSH
ssh -i landing-transform-keypair.pem ubuntu@<EC2-PUBLIC-IP>

# Download AWS CLI v2
curl 'https://awscli.amazonaws.com/awscli-exe-linux-x86_64.zip' -o 'awscliv2.zip'

# Install unzip
sudo apt install unzip -y

# Unzip the package
unzip awscliv2.zip

# Install AWS CLI
sudo ./aws/install

# Verify installation
aws --version

Step 1.3 – Configure AWS CLI

aws configure
# Enter when prompted:
# AWS Access Key ID:     <your-access-key>
# AWS Secret Access Key: <your-secret-key>
# Default region name:   us-east-1
# Default output format: json

Step 1.4 – Install kubectl

# Download kubectl
curl -LO 'https://dl.k8s.io/release/$(curl -s https://dl.k8s.io/release/stable.txt)/bin/linux/amd64/kubectl'

# Make it executable
chmod +x kubectl

# Move to PATH
sudo mv kubectl /usr/local/bin/

# Verify
kubectl version --client

Step 1.5 – Install Helm

# Download Helm install script
curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/helm/helm/main/scripts/get-helm-3 | bash

# Verify
helm version

Step 1.6 – Install eksctl & Create EKS Cluster

# Install eksctl
curl --silent --location 'https://github.com/weaveworks/eksctl/releases/latest/download/eksctl_Linux_amd64.tar.gz' | tar xz -C /tmp
sudo mv /tmp/eksctl /usr/local/bin

# Create EKS Cluster
eksctl create cluster \
  --name landing-transform-my-eks-cluster \
  --region us-east-1

# Verify nodes are ready
kubectl get nodes
💡 Cluster creation takes 15–20 minutes. Wait until all nodes show STATUS = Ready.

Step 1.7 – Deploy Prometheus via Helm

# Create Prometheus namespace
kubectl create namespace prometheus

# Add Prometheus Helm repo
helm repo add prometheus https://prometheus-community.github.io/helm-charts

# List repos to verify
helm repo ls

# Update repos
helm repo update

# Deploy Prometheus
helm install prometheus-deployment prometheus/prometheus \
  --namespace prometheus \
  --set alertmanager.persistentVolume.storageClass='openebs-hostpath' \
  --set server.persistentVolume.storageClass='openebs-hostpath'

# Verify Prometheus pods
kubectl get pods -n prometheus

# Get Prometheus service (copy the LoadBalancer URL)
kubectl get svc -n prometheus
💡 Access Prometheus in browser using the LoadBalancer external URL on port 80.

 
PART 2 — Deploy Grafana & Import Dashboard

Step 2.1 – Create Prometheus DataSource File

Create the file prometheus-datasource.yaml before deploying Grafana:

# Create the datasource YAML file
vi prometheus-datasource.yaml

# Paste the following content:
apiVersion: 1
datasources:
  - name: Prometheus
    type: prometheus
    url: http://prometheus-deployment-server.prometheus.svc.cluster.local
    access: proxy
    isDefault: true

Step 2.2 – Deploy Grafana via Helm

# Create Grafana namespace
kubectl create namespace grafana

# Add Grafana Helm repo
helm repo add grafana https://grafana.github.io/helm-charts

# Update repos
helm repo update

# Deploy Grafana with all settings
helm install grafana grafana/grafana \
  --namespace grafana \
  --set persistence.storageClassName='openebs-hostpath' \
  --set persistence.enabled=true \
  --set adminPassword='secret' \
  --values prometheus-datasource.yaml \
  --set service.type=LoadBalancer

Step 2.3 – Verify Grafana Deployment

# Check all Grafana pods/services
kubectl get all -n grafana

# Check Persistent Volume Claim
kubectl get pvc -n grafana

# Get Grafana admin password
kubectl get secret --namespace grafana grafana \
  -o jsonpath='{.data.admin-password}' | base64 --decode

# Get Grafana LoadBalancer URL
kubectl get svc -n grafana

Step 2.4 – Access & Configure Grafana Dashboard

#	Action	Command / Detail
1	Open Browser	Go to: http://<GRAFANA-LOADBALANCER-URL>
2	Login	Username: admin   |   Password: secret (or from Step 2.3)
3	Go to Dashboards	Click Menu → Dashboards → New → Import
4	Import Dashboard	Enter Dashboard ID: 6417  → Click 'Load'
5	Select Datasource	Choose 'prometheus-default' from the dropdown
6	Click Import	Dashboard is now live with cluster metrics

💡 Dashboard 6417 (by secca1) shows: CPU utilization, Memory usage, Disk usage, Pod count, Node status, and Container running state.

 
PART 3 — HPA (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler) & Load Testing

Step 3.1 – Verify Metrics Server

# Check metrics-server is running (required for HPA)
kubectl get pods -n kube-system | grep metrics-server

Step 3.2 – Create & Deploy the HPA Application

Create hpa.yaml with a Deployment + LoadBalancer Service:

# Create HPA manifest
vi hpa.yaml

# The file should contain:
# - A Deployment named: hpa-deploy
# - A Service of type: LoadBalancer

# Apply the manifest
kubectl apply -f hpa.yaml

# Verify pod and deployment
kubectl get pod,deploy,svc

Step 3.3 – Create Horizontal Pod Autoscaler

# Create HPA for the deployment
kubectl autoscale deployment hpa-deploy \
  --cpu-percent=50 \
  --min=1 \
  --max=10

# Verify HPA is created
kubectl get hpa

# Watch HPA live (open Terminal 1)
kubectl get hpa -w

Step 3.4 – Generate Load (Open Terminal 2)

# Run load generator in a new terminal
kubectl run load-generator \
  --image=busybox \
  --restart=Never \
  -- /bin/sh -c 'while true; do wget -q -O- http://<LOAD-BALANCER-URL>; done'

# Watch pods scale up in Terminal 1
kubectl get pods -w

# Check CPU utilization goes above 50% threshold
kubectl get hpa -w
💡 CPU utilization will jump (e.g. 0% → 179% → 250%). HPA will automatically scale from 1 pod up to 10 pods based on threshold.

Step 3.5 – Observe in Grafana Dashboard

#	Action	Command / Detail
1	Open Grafana	Go to Dashboard 6417 in browser
2	Refresh	Click refresh icon or set auto-refresh to 5 min
3	Watch Pod Count	Cluster Pod Capacity graph shows pods increasing
4	Watch CPU	CPU utilization graph spikes during load generation
5	Delete HPA	kubectl delete hpa hpa-deploy   →   pods scale back down
6	Re-observe	Dashboard shows pod count decreasing after HPA deleted

Step 3.6 – Cleanup Load Test Resources

# Delete the load generator pod
kubectl delete pod load-generator

# Delete HPA
kubectl delete hpa hpa-deploy

# (Optional) Delete HPA application
kubectl delete -f hpa.yaml

 
PART 4 — Cleanup (Uninstall Everything)

💡 Always clean up in this order: Helm releases → PVCs → EKS Cluster → EC2 Instance

Step 4.1 – Uninstall Prometheus

# List Prometheus Helm release
helm ls -n prometheus

# Uninstall Prometheus
helm uninstall prometheus-deployment -n prometheus

# Verify nothing remains
kubectl get all -n prometheus

Step 4.2 – Uninstall Grafana

# List Grafana Helm release
helm ls -n grafana

# Uninstall Grafana
helm uninstall grafana -n grafana

# Verify nothing remains
kubectl get all -n grafana

Step 4.3 – Delete Remaining Services & PVCs

# Check all resources across all namespaces
kubectl get all -A

# Delete any leftover LoadBalancer services manually
kubectl delete svc <service-name> -n grafana

# Check PVCs
kubectl get pvc -n prometheus
kubectl get pvc -n grafana

# Delete PVCs
kubectl delete pvc <pvc-name> -n prometheus
kubectl delete pvc <pvc-name> -n grafana

# Verify all deleted
kubectl get all -A

Step 4.4 – Delete HPA Application (if not done in Part 3)

# Delete HPA and deployment
kubectl delete -f hpa.yaml

# Verify default namespace is clean
kubectl get all

Step 4.5 – Delete EKS Cluster

# Delete the EKS cluster
eksctl delete cluster \
  --name landing-transform-my-eks-cluster \
  --region us-east-1

# Verify deletion in AWS Console:
# Go to → EKS → Elastic Kubernetes Service → US East 1
# Status should change to: Deleting → then disappear

Step 4.6 – Terminate EC2 Instance

#	Action	Command / Detail
1	Open AWS Console	Go to EC2 → Instances
2	Select Instance	Select: landing-transform instance
3	Terminate	Instance State → Terminate Instance → Confirm
4	Delete Key Pair	Go to Key Pairs → Select landing-transform-keypair → Actions → Delete

✅ Cleanup Complete — Summary

Resource	Status
Prometheus (Helm release)	✅ Deleted
Grafana (Helm release)	✅ Deleted
Persistent Volume Claims	✅ Deleted
HPA + Application	✅ Deleted
EKS Cluster	✅ Deleted
EC2 Instance	✅ Deleted
Key Pair	✅ Deleted



